    {
      "id": "b04fb8f8dffd3c7b4885e2aeeb23866a7a1950c7",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2011-11-03 03:46:21.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI think this does not increase too much memory usage, does it?\nOverflow is currently only a handful of bytes, but still.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "65f8b0df90135e16daf5aee59ed84b313843d145",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-11-03 03:51:44.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\n",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "d97295dc7d1167eccb0dc44b7e5d06d6f7f44db5",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 2,
        "name": "Jenkins",
        "username": "hudson",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-11-03 04:39:52.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Verified\n\nBuild Successful \n \nhttp://build.whamcloud.com/job/lustre-reviews/3084/ : SUCCESS",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "f7e4ff3d2ccc7ad460db25502e6e40ef82b0573a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-11-03 04:45:03.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nOleg, do you know how much memory is used here?  I'd be hesitant to double the memory allocation for a rare case.  Is it worthwhile to track down the debug message that is causing the problem and rather make that shorter?\n\nLooking at osc_page_print() it certainly seems to be printing an excessive amount of information.  Could this be split into five separate calls to (*printer) so that each call does not need such a huge buffer?  Even better would probably just be printing less data, since it seems like most of this will not be useful for the large majority of cases.\n\nI don't know enough about this code to actually render a code review (this is the first time I even see it), but allocating more memory never seems like a good idea.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "2ef7bcede2a53ab9ec68a5928d1aa70c5f6b742d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2011-11-03 05:07:28.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nHow much memory is used where? In this offending print? seems to be under 260 bytes, which does not mean it might not be a bit higher when I am not looking.\nIt is likely that upping the limit to say 300 bytes will suffice as well.\nI believe these \"keys\" are allocatd once per lustre-using process, so it should not be terribly bad most of the time.\n\nUnfortunately splitting the call to *printer won't help at all.\n\nThe *printer fills an internal buffer (the one referenced by the key increased) until a \\n is seen at the end.\nSo unless we want to split that one line output into several, it won't work.\n\nPrinting less data is a double edged sword too. Sure we don't need it most of the time, but what about when we do need it?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "0c8ee8e7ddbf58ce900f203c7fe6cc085a6bd371",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2011-11-03 14:38:52.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Verified\n\nTests received by maloo, run on rhel/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/29838404-0628-11e1-b578-52540025f9af).  Ran 13 tests.  No failures.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "d6bc7df4b17a821e2de3e0c27457869e6827c1ab",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-12-06 16:32:16.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI do not oppose to increase the LU_CDEBUG_LINE to hold more message. What  my concern is that do we know how much buffer is enough for that? currently, it is about 300 bytes, but what about for more message in future? \n\nSo I think whether it is possible to introduce some adjustable mechanism to process such rare large buffer cases. In fact, we have some similar process for \"mdd_links_get()\", in such case, we just allocate normal size buffer at the beginning, and enlarge the buffer when needed.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "b543755ed1a4a3d425a4e20ab1130ff07fafc8b3",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2011-12-12 18:01:37.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, approved\n\n",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
